Descriptive statistics and tables

Antoine JARDIN

18 septembre 2015

install.packages("ggplot2")
install.packages("xtable")

you may need to select a mirror from which R will download the required package
Pick lyon as it is close to Paris/Reims.

Were loading a few libraries

library(ggplot2)
library(xtable)

Here were extracting a dataset from the ggplot2 package

data(diamonds)
df <- diamonds

Were checking the head of the dataframe

Each row is an observation, each column is a variable

head(df)
##   carat       cut color clarity depth table price    x    y    z
## 1  0.23     Ideal     E     SI2  61.5    55   326 3.95 3.98 2.43
## 2  0.21   Premium     E     SI1  59.8    61   326 3.89 3.84 2.31

## 6  0.24 Very Good     J    VVS2  62.8    57   336 3.94 3.96 2.48

Here are the names of the colums

colnames(df)
##  [1] "carat"   "cut"     "color"   "clarity" "depth"   "table"   "price"

Lets make a frequency table of color (variable of df)

table(df$color)
## 
##     D     E     F     G     H     I     J 
##  6775  9797  9542 11292  8304  5422  2808

We can display it in columns if we transform it into a dataframe

tab <- as.data.frame(table(df$color))

tab
##   Var1  Freq
## 1    D  6775
## 2    E  9797
## 3    F  9542
## 4    G 11292
## 5    H  8304
## 6    I  5422
## 7    J  2808

Lets make a crosstab

color will be the x variable

cut will be the y variable

table(df$color, df$cut)
##    
##     Fair Good Very Good Premium Ideal
##   D  163  662      1513    1603  2834
##   E  224  933      2400    2337  3903
##   F  312  909      2164    2331  3826
##   G  314  871      2299    2924  4884
##   H  303  702      1824    2360  3115
##   I  175  522      1204    1428  2093
##   J  119  307       678     808   896

We can store the result and display it nicely with the ftable() function

table1 <- table(df$color, df$cut)
ftable(table1)
##    Fair Good Very Good Premium Ideal
##                                     
## D   163  662      1513    1603  2834
## E   224  933      2400    2337  3903

## I   175  522      1204    1428  2093
## J   119  307       678     808   896

Now we use prop.table to compute the cell percentages for our table

prop.table(table(df$color, df$cut))
##    
##            Fair        Good   Very Good     Premium       Ideal
##   D 0.003021876 0.012272896 0.028049685 0.029718205 0.052539859
##   E 0.004152762 0.017296997 0.044493882 0.043325918 0.072358176
##   F 0.005784205 0.016852058 0.040118650 0.043214683 0.070930664
##   G 0.005821283 0.016147571 0.042621431 0.054208380 0.090545050
##   H 0.005617353 0.013014461 0.033815350 0.043752317 0.057749351
##   I 0.003244346 0.009677419 0.022321098 0.026473860 0.038802373
##   J 0.002206155 0.005691509 0.012569522 0.014979607 0.016611049

Using (,1) and (,2) options will compute row and column percentages

prop.table(table(df$color, df$cut), 1)
##    
##           Fair       Good  Very Good    Premium      Ideal
##   D 0.02405904 0.09771218 0.22332103 0.23660517 0.41830258
##   E 0.02286414 0.09523323 0.24497295 0.23854241 0.39838726

prop.table(table(df$color, df$cut), 2)

Using margin.table will compute marginal values for rows and columns following the same logic

margin.table(table(df$color, df$cut), 1)
## 
##     D     E     F     G     H     I     J 
##  6775  9797  9542 11292  8304  5422  2808
margin.table(table(df$color, df$cut), 2)
## 
##      Fair      Good Very Good   Premium     Ideal 
##      1610      4906     12082     13791     21551

We can plot the table with ggplot2

p <- ggplot(df, aes(x=cut, y=color))
p + geom_tile(aes(fill=color, size=color))

Lets look at quantitative variables

We use the function summary() to display several basic descriptive statistics

summary(df$price)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

With the xtable library, we can also use the function xtabs

This function can be used for three-way frequency table and more

It uses a new kind of object, which is called a formula

[ ~ cut + color ] is the formula

[ df ] is the source dataframe

mytab <- xtabs(~ cut + color, data=df)
ftable(mytab)
##           color    D    E    F    G    H    I    J
## cut                                               
## Fair             163  224  312  314  303  175  119
## Good             662  933  909  871  702  522  307
## Very Good       1513 2400 2164 2299 1824 1204  678
## Premium         1603 2337 2331 2924 2360 1428  808
## Ideal           2834 3903 3826 4884 3115 2093  896

Of course we can use all other techniques to the result of the xtabs() function

ftable(prop.table(mytab,1))

Graphics

We compute the cut histogram and display it

m <- ggplot(df, aes(x=cut))
m + geom_histogram()

Lets do it for the price variable (quantitative)

m2 <- ggplot(df, aes(x=price))
m2 + geom_histogram()
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

Changing the binwidth will define the resolution

m2 + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1)

m2 + geom_histogram(binwidth = 10)

m2 + geom_histogram(binwidth = 100)

Of course we can add facetting

m2 + geom_histogram(binwidth = 100) + facet_wrap(~cut)

m2 + geom_histogram(binwidth = 100) + facet_wrap(~cut, ncol=5)

Next week, well look at the vcd() library

It will help us compute association indicators

It can also produce intuitive graphs to represent crosstabs and associations
